reviewText: 4.8 starsRango is no kids' flick, but it is a mature masterpiece in a whole bunch of ways that will soon make it a major cult favorite, guaranteed. It takes a certain sense of humor to dig this one, but if you've got it, you're in for a big big treat. Rango also has one of the best-looking, most detailed blu-ray transfers I've yet seen.A partial remake of Chinatown with existential overtones and psychedelic undercurrent with nods to dozens of cinematic classics, this "cartoon" Western satire has a lot more in common with Bugs Bunny and his anarchic freakiness than with any of the new crop of Pixar etc family animation works, great as they can be (Up, Incredibles). It also has Roger Rabbit's tantalizing self-reflexivity in spades and glittering diamonds. Rango salutes HST in its first scene and then goes waaaay off into left field, climbs into the bleachers, gets a beer, watches the relievers warm up, and finally scampers back down into right field and is kicked out of the ball park.For me it was a major treat, as I love Thompson, Chinatown, Warner Bros cartoons, and intelligent insanity in general. Rango piles on so many genres and ideas and spoofed cliches and wowza that your head is spinning most of the time, even if just from the truly amazing animation quality and endless wild concepts. Logan's script is so much brighter and sharper than almost anything being made lately that it seems an anachronism; its levels of thought will take your brain to many literate, self-aware clouds floating by your mind's eye.Verbinski directs the proceedings with similar aplomb, and Depp shows more voice and character range than in almost anything he's ever done. Ned Beatty is another standout, but everyone is excellent. And the various little conspiracy nods are all too accurate; there's a lot going on in Rango, and multiple viewings will show many layers of crisp detail, visually and intellectually. One might even call this a kaleidoscopic environmentalist's lament, a world-weary nod to how close to the brink we really are and a reminder that there are many other worlds out there and in here, so let's watch it Buddha-like with as much compassionate detachment as is musterable. Whatevar that means!And eye candy? Man, this is the handmade organic 75% cacao chocogasm of eye candy. Soooo much detail in some of the animals' hair and eyes that it sets a new standard (can't wait to see it in 3D). This will show off your flat screen in ways you'd never imagined. It's so good I unplugged my PS3 and took it to a friend's place just so he could see how good his flat screen can look. I wouldn't go to that trouble for just any film.Nor would I watch it twice in two days. I haven't done that in years, in fact. But I just had to check to see if Rango was as beguilingly weird and wonderful by daylight as it was late at night, and indeed it is.Rango is bound to be hailed as one of the great toon films of all time, methinks, and I'd rank it with Roger Rabbit, the best Bugs (high praise, bub!), Up and a very few other animated masterpieces. Is it for kids? Not really, unless you'd like to raise them to be smarter and more self-aware than the average little texting robots these days, so, you know, be careful! I think many kids are much brighter much earlier than we think, but then again I watched a lot of Bugs as a kid, so I may be biased.If you've got a blu-ray player, at least rent this just to see how good your screen can look. And if you happen to get your mind blown in the process, well, lucky you! It beats being a thirsty lizard in an aloha shirt.
summary: Fear and Loathing with Sartre in Chinatown; incredibly crisp animation with a startlingly intelligent script

reviewText: Unbelievably funny satire on everything from acting to westerns,from directing to good storytelling. Even the music makes fun of the music in classic westerns, to great effect.I'd watch this gem over and over just to get all the jokes I missed the first time. i'm sure I'll be buying this one. It's a classic. Like SCREAM was to horror films, RANGO is to westerns.Good story. Great acting. Great satire. Fun for all.

reviewText: I expected a lot from the duo Verbinski/Depp and I was not disappointed. Both me and my 10 y.o. daughter we spend a great cinema moment together watching "Rango" and I recommend this movie for a whole family evening, as it is a typical "kidult" (kid+adult) movie. In fact, when I looked, there were more adults than kids in the cinema and they were all having a really great time!The reasons why this movie is so good are many, and I will try to enumerate the more important, avoiding the spoilers as much as possible:1) It is a really really good, solid classical western, with all the necessary ingredients: a lawless town (named Dirt), a mysterious lone stranger, a cemetery filled with dead sheriffs, a cute (although tough) senorita in dire straits, a bank robbery, a saloon filled with the scum of the earth, a joyful merry undertaker (which is only normal - his is the only prospering business in Dirt), a deadly evil gunfighter who ALWAYS "takes a soul" in every town he visits, an Indian tracker (who molts, but we shall not hold it against him, shall we?) and also desperadoes, buzzards, posses, dynamite, old timers with shotguns, youngsters with Colts, hillbillies with Gatling machine guns, booze galore, Far West stories, coffee and beans around a campfire, mariachis on the cactuses and let's not forget the seven brothers killed with one bullet...)))2) Johny Depp gives to Rango more than just his voice - this lizard IS Johny Depp! And also by placing in his mouth some of the lines from "Pirates of the Caribbean", Johny Depp made me relieve some of the best moments of this franchise. There were moments when I half expected seeing Barbossa behind that Gatling machine gun!3) The Spirit of the West - as a wise old armadillo called Roadkill teaches Rango, "the Spirit of the West rides in a white chariot with a guard of golden warriors" - and indeed he does! And I guarantee you that when you finally meet yourself the Spirit of the West you will spill the soda on your pants and choke on your popcorn, like half of the public did (me included) when we were watching it in the cinema! I almost died laughing at this moment (although my daughter did not get the joke - and I think most of the kids will not get it either). No more spoilers here about The Spirit of the West!4) Visually and graphically this is a very well done movie, quite unique in style, unlike anything else made by Pixar or Dreamworks. In fact I really hope that Nickelodeon Movies will carry on, because this style of movie making completes very pleasantly the offer on the market of kid (and kidult) movies. VERY good job on the visual aspect of this movie!To keep the things short I will not say much more and I will just invite you to see it in the cinema if you still can and then to enjoy it on DVD. And I am all in favor of a sequel, in which we could hear for example an old grumpy one eyed rat saying: "Fill yer hands, rascals!" before charging ahead with his Colts blazing!
summary: Discover your inner lizard and hit the Dirt, gringo - but beware of bullets, buzzards, bats and bullfrogs by bushels!

reviewText: There's a lot for adults, especially film buffs, to like about "Rango." Rango, a lizard like no lizard you've ever seen, lives in a terrarium with a wind-up goldfish and a headless nude Barbie-style doll, acting out little dramas he dreams up with his plastic friends. One day his world is literally shattered as the terrarium falls out of the back of the family station wagon and breaks on a little-traveled road in the middle of the Mojave Desert. Rango finds himself in Dirt, a town running out of water and in desperate need of a hero. The acting skills Rango honed in his terrarium enable him to convince the townsfolk that he's a hero. Now he has to find out if he can really be the hero they need.The plot, such as it is, is a pastiche of "High Noon," Clint Eastwood spaghetti westerns, and especially "Chinatown." If you are not familiar with these decidedly adult-oriented films, much of the pleasure of "Rango" will be lost on you. The cleverly derivative script is filled with verbal gymnastics and philosophy served up by a roadkill armadillo and a Man With No Name.I can't even come up with a word that doesn't sound trite to describe the animation--WOW!! This is a fabulous movie to look at. Every character has so much detail and originality. Coen Brothers stalwart Roger Deakins acted as the cinematography consultant and it shows in every frame. Johnny Depp heads a voice cast of great actors including Ned Beatty and Harry Dean Stanton."Rango" has enough physical humor and action to keep my eight-year-old entertained, but I know many of the jokes and all of the classic film references went over his head. The language is nothing my kid does not hear in a traffic jam, and to the extent the humor is crude, it is usually expressed with such sophisticated wordplay that I did not find it particularly offensive. There was a big chase scene, a cast-of-thousands set piece of the type in which director Gore Verbinski specializes in the "Pirates of the Caribbean," that is uncomfortably violent. There are also pleasantly surprising moments of quiet reflection and introspection that, based on the relatively cartoonish quality of the "Pirates" movies, I did not expect from Verbinski.I can enthusiastically recommend Rango for film buffs and for kids whose parents are not highly protective when it comes to mild swearing and violence. I ended with a four-star rating because, although Rango is surprisingly thoughtful and beautifully done in many ways, it bothered me that instead of having a wholly original story, they cobbled the script together from the plots of other movies. Forget it Jake. It's Chinatown.
summary: Enjoyable Pastiche of Classic Films May Go Over Kids' Heads

reviewText: You never know what to expect from Johnny Depp.  The Mad Hatter,  Willy Wonka.  Jack Sparrow.  Ed Wood.  Barnabas Collins.  Tonto.  Sweeney Todd.  Has any other contemporary actor been as diverse or risk-taking as Depp?  Maybe Meryl Streep.Add RANGO the wisecracking talking chameleon to his growing list.  RANGO is immensely enjoyable and it's not a Pixar, Dreamworks or Disney!  It's really aimed at adult audiences but kids will enjoy the bizarre and eccentric characters and will most likely scream in terror at one of animation's vilest villains--Jake the Rattlesnake.RANGO;s director, Gore Verbanski (sp) expertly pays homage to both traditional and spaghetti westerns and the production team paints a marvelous landscape in the town of Dirt.  Hans Zimmer composed a great score to punctuate the movie and the owl storytellers a brilliant addition.While the movie belongs to Depp, the other voice actors are very good:  Isla Fisher, Ned Beatty, Bill Nighy, Ray Winstone, Abigail Breslin, Alfred Molina and Timothy Olyphant.RANGO is great entertainment and will deservedly get an Oscar nomination.  A sequel?  Hmmm...

reviewText: The previews would have kept me away from Rango but the many rapturous reviews brought me in to see it. Really, a pretty amazing accomplishment. Obviously a lot of critics were won over by the many, many references to other films - which I feel went a bit far and began interfering with my involvement in the movie I was actually watching. Being based to such a great degree on Chinatown probably elevated it in many of those critics eyes as well but, since I don't really care for Chinatown, while I could appreciate the references, I wished that, if the filmmakers needed to copy a classic film, they had copied a one I like. The performances were uniformly great and the animation, not of the flashy "look what we can do" sort, was truly amazing, especially when I attended to all of the near photographically real elements at play.ILM will have a tough time topping this with their second animated film whatever it is.

reviewText: I had to see this movie a second time to catch all of the inside jokes and adult humor.  Although rated PG much of it is risqué in a subtle way.  For parents who watch films with kids, this is one of the best.  The kiddies won't understand much of the humor, but the parents will be laughing.Rango (voiced by Johnny Depp) is a chameleon on a road trip with his owners when he is unceremoniously bounced off the vehicle in the middle of the desert.  Not used to the barren, hot surroundings he encounters a string of friendly animals (Alfred Molina is great as "Roadkill") as well as not so friendly predators before finding his way to Dirt, a dying town full of worn out talking animals.  One is a cute female lizard of some type (tan rather than green) named Beans (Isla Fisher).Dirt's water supply has been cut off and the town and inhabitants are withering away.  Rango is appointed sheriff and vows to find out what happened to the water.  It turns out that the town's mayor (Ned Beatty, a turtle) has diverted the water to supply a big city (Las Vegas) nearby.  Rango, Beans and others search for a way to get the water back to town and encounter Balthazar, a shrew (Harry Dean Stanton) who is believed to be the culprit along with his numerous "relatives."  These scenes are fast moving, hilarious and look great.This all leads to a not surprising conclusion when the mayor brings in Rattlesnake Jake (the great Bill Nighy) to confront Rango and Beans who is the lone holdout to sell her property.  Recommended for kids and adults.I would urge you to get the Blu ray version of this movie (I have the one that includes an extended cut).  It is spectacular in every sense of the word.  It happens I was test driving this movie on a new display with a new player and AV receiver and couldn't have picked a better film.  The video comes in 1080p resolution and a 2.40:1 aspect ratio.  Every animated skin bump, hair, dirt are shockingly clear and colorful.  Likewise the audio is perfection.  Check out the DTS-HD Master Audio 5.1 for another example of as good as it gets.  Crisp and clear throughout, the soundtrack is properly center and the use of the surrounds and sub is appropriate for the scenes.  Quiet sounds like a fly buzzing, a fan moving are perfectly executed.  Both the video and audio are demo grade.  The film has Spanish, Portuguese, English SDH and French subtitles available.  Here are the extras:*Audio Commentary (Only available on extended version): Director, Story Co-Writer, & Producer Gore Verbinski and other technical supervisors.*Breaking the Rules: Making Animation History (1080p, 48:52)*Deleted Scenes (1080p, 8:27)*Real Creatures of Dirt (1080p, 22:16)*Storyboard Reel Picture-in-Picture (Only available on theatrical version)*A Field Trip to Dirt (1080p)*Rango Theatrical Trailer (1080p, 2:27).*Digital Copy*DVD Copy.
summary: (BLU RAY REVIEW) Demo quality and very funny

reviewText: Rango is one of the most pleasantly weird animated movies I've ever seen. It's basically a throwback western with enough grit to make Rooster Cogburn blush.The visuals are gorgeous, courtesy of ILM (this being their first animated feature), with some of the characters looking more Muppet like than a creation of CGI. Maybe the closest I've seen to reaching the high standards of Pixar, but boy are they not pretty to look at. You can practically smell them.The story is very simple and similar to almost every western made, but the various strange looking inhabitants and clever dialogue carry most of the film. And yes, it's more clever than laugh out loud funny. In fact, most of the jokes seemed to have been missed by the people sitting around me. They are quick and often thrown out with a strong accent so you'll have to really pay attention.The voice cast is full of familiar names, but Johnny Depp as the title character deserves mention. He could have phoned this thing in and still made millions, but instead it seems that he put every ounce of energy and craft he possessed in creating a voice that's both memorable and interesting to listen to.This may seem strange, but Rango isn't made with kids in mind. Almost all of the jokes and references are aimed at adults. Likewise, the language, violence and all around meanness will likely upset small children and the parents that might be caught off guard. If The Dark Knight was a hard PG-13, this pushes PG to the limits. Some older kids might enjoy it, but like I said, most just won't get it.If it doesn't get forgotten due to the early release date, this could pop up for an animated film Oscar. It is not for everyone, so maybe that's why I found it so fresh and captivating.
summary: The Ugly, the Ugly and the Ugly

reviewText: When you think of the heavy hitters in the animated feature film realm, it's certainly understandable if the first things that come to mind are Disney, Pixar or DreamWorks.  However Nickelodeon has been hovering around the scene for a while now, hoping to earn a nice piece of the CG animated movie pie.Rango is by far their most serious attempt and while the film's deserved PG-13 rating may succeed at distancing it from its key demographic (a concept all studios would be wise to emulate from industry-leader Pixar).The story follows the comical, transformative journey of Rango (Depp), a sheltered chameleon living as an ordinary family pet, while facing a major identity crisis.  After all, how high can you aim when your whole purpose in life is to blend in?  When Rango accidentally winds up in the gritty, gun-slinging town of Dirt, a lawless outpost populated by the desert's wiliest whimsical creatures, the less-than-courageous lizard suddenly finds that he's been preparing for this role his whole life.  Welcomed as the last hope the whole town has been awaiting, the newly appointed Sheriff Rango is forced to play his new role as if it life depended on it.  In fact, it does!  In a blaze of action-packed situations and encounters with outrageous characters, Rango starts to become the hero he's always pretended to be.If you didn't already know, this piece represents Gore Verbinski's first film since concluding his Pirates of the Caribbean trilogy in 2007 and represented an ideal opportunity for him to continue working with the oddly charismatic Johnny Depp.Like the Pirates trilogy, Verbinski proves strangely proficient at developing properties that seem almost kid-friendly but continually flirt with adult-only ideals and references.  In fact those viewers expecting a wild-west themed variation of a typical Disney/ Pixar feature will be in for a bit of rude awakening.  Rather than craft an action-driven kids movie peppered with adult humor and pop culture references, Rango is boldly unrepentant for the various tones and complexities it explores.Industrial Light and Magic does a spectacular job with the look of the film, with drab landscapes and gritty character textures and while the John Logan script is funny at times, appreciation of this film depends heavily on the viewer's feeling towards old spaghetti westerns.The pacing is deliberately drawn out and littered with crusty townsfolk, children will likely find the prose a bit too dull to hold their interest even before the objectionable language and references have a chance to upset them.  In fact, a strong argument could be made that this is very nearly like watching a genuine old western film with personified animals transplanted over black and white live action sequences.  Further contributing to the sensation is an extended version release on the DVD & Blu-Ray that comes in at just under two-hours.I personally enjoyed the idea of a desert down finding so much value in water that it has literally become currency and there's no denying that, while a bit hideous, there is some serious brilliance in the character design models.Of course despite the film's rambling philosophies and lackluster supporting characters, Rango has its moments thanks in no small part to solid vocal deliveries from Depp, Ned Beatty, and Wedding Crashers' Isla Fisher.There are some slapstick moments to keep the kiddies in their seats even if the western puns and clichés will be lost upon them.  Adults may get a kick out of a few of the exchanges although truthfully, they can be a bit over the top, eliciting some "ewwws" even out of teens at times.In conclusion some of the finest computer generated visuals to date (there is a segment depicting a human that is nearly photo-realistic), Rango lacks the type of cleverness that makes many of Pixar and DreamWorks' pieces so timeless.  Adults who appreciate modern animation (especially those with a fondness for western classics) will find much to enjoy here but contrary to the Nickelodeon backing, kids aren't the target audience for this one.
summary: Thematic, Pretty And Not For Everyone

reviewText: Rango is, in many respects, a typical western flick. (some spoilers) Evil rich guy controlling the water supply in order to buy up everyone's property...smart talking, tough as nails cowgirl...your typical handful of thugs, villains, drifters, ne'erdowells, ranchers and cowhands...only thing is, this movie is about a chameleon, cats, lizards, snakes, etc. Bizarre? Nah. It's really pretty good.The film is a parody of westerns, and as such gets away with all the things that real westerns don't. The humor is good -- nothing outrageously funny, but some solid laughs. The movie is a little slow out of the gate, but picks up speed right quick. * ahem * Anyhow, the pace picks up, and the laughs start coming pretty steadily, after the first half hour or so.This is not the funniest movie you're likely to see. It's not even the funniest put out recently. And, no, just because it's animated, it's not necessarily a kid's movie. There are darker themes touched on, and the pace is such that younger kids might find themselves bored quickly. This is an animated films for grown ups and young adults more than kids. And it is a good one.Would definitely recommend for those seeking a light-hearted, amusing film. 4/5, for a solid, fun western parody.
summary: A film that turns all of the flaws of the western genre into gold...

reviewText: I had a lot of fun watching Rango, though little kids won't get all the film references (especially Chinatown). Not to worry, excellent animation, a first for ILM, and terrific characters, all endearing, led by a confident and sincere Johnny Depp. It's all about good and evil, and good intentions not always well-planned. Poor Rango...will he survive?It's loaded with great stock characters from classic films of yore, and some moments of ILM brilliance had you on location, a bit of realism added to the mix. I'm glad I watched this film, since many critics didn't like it. It's since won most of the Animated Feature awards, after Tintin's disqualification for being action/play.Maybe not the greatest, but I especially liked the references to Chinatown, Toy Story, spaghetti westerns (with an appearance by a simulated Clint Eastwood), The Milagro Beanfield War, and many others. Film freaks will have a field day guessing, while enjoying a terrific ensemble cast having nothing but fun. Little kids may not get the cleverness of it all, but the good vs evil element may be a fine lesson; also a good lesson about integrity.The non-intrusive musical moments were quite enjoyable.I apparently got more out of it than most...

reviewText: I'm not sure what all the negative fuss is about.  What is a "kids" movie, anyway?  Recognizing that appreciation of humor differs, I laughed a lot at this movie, as did my 22 year old daughter.  My in-laws, who are in their eighties, perhaps not so much.  I found the dialogue clever and witty, the photography stunning, and the voice acting terrific.  This film is rated PG, which I would say warns parents of young children to check it out before they expose their children to it. My opinion is that it is perfectly appropriate for age 10 and above (Netflix Common Sense rating says ok for 9+).Remembering back to films with adult themes I thought exciting and entertaining as a kid, I think of Ben-Hur, Guns of Navarone, Jason and the Argonauts, Hondo and Rio Bravo.  I'm talking about such themes as self sacrifice, bravery in the face of danger, self doubt, and good versus evil.  This film has all of those themes and presents them in an exciting, funny and entertaining manner.  No, I would not take a five year old to see this. I took my daughter to see The Lion King and Beauty and the Beast when she was likely a little young for them.  She was scared a few times, but entertained. Consider the Star Wars films, or the Toy Story trilogy, which also present many of the same themes, and which are considered good "family")as opposed to "children's) films. Consider the brilliantly animated films of Hayao Miyazaki, most of which are also rated PG, but universally praised as great family films.I urge anyone who really likes movies, especially Westerns, to see this film.  If you're wondering if this is appropriate for your children or grandchildren, check it out first.  My opinion is that if you disregard the rating system, and simply assume that a film is appropriate just because it's animated, then any bad surprise is on your own head. You want a good movie for young children, check out Winnie the Pooh.

reviewText: Hollywood heavyweight Johnny Depp and director Gore Verbinski (Pirates of the Caribbean) team up to bring the tale of the most unlikely hero of the Old West in the critically acclaimed animated comedy hit Rango. An oddball pet chameleon (Depp) is accidentally left stranded in the middle of the scorching Mojave Desert and wanders to a small town inhabited by desert animals, where he assumes the identity of a tough drifter named Rango. After killing a fierce hawk out of sheer dumb luck, Rango is named the town's newest sheriff, and attempts to solve the water shortage that has placed the town in the brink of despair. Rango is the funniest animated family movie of 2011. Verbinski delivers a crowd-pleasing animated spectacle with a fun-filled storyline, amusing characters, stunning computer animation and a fine comical performance by Johnny Depp. Rango also features the voice talents of Isla Fisher, Abigail Breslin, Ned Beatty, Alfred Molina, Bill Nighy, Stephen Root, Harry Dean Stanton and Timothy Olyphant.It wouldn't be right calling the Blu-ray release of Rango anything but one of the best Blu-rays of the year. The theatrical and extended versions are included in this release. The animated comedy is presented in a 2.40:1 widescreen format. The 1080p transfer is absolutely flawless and gorgeous. The DTS-HD Master Audio soundtrack will surely satisfy the needs of home theater enthusiasts. The Blu-ray includes a fine selection of bonus features like an audio commentary track by director Gore Verbinski and production crew, the 2-part making-of featurette "Breaking the Rules: Making Animation History", 8 and a half minutes of deleted scenes, picture-in-picture storyboards, and a n interactive tour of the town of Dirt and its townsfolk. Overall, Rango scores an "A-".
summary: Meet the most unlikely Hero of the Old West

reviewText: Where to begin with Rango? I intentionally avoided it when it was in theaters for no good reason, other than the fact that I knew I would buy it when it came out on Blu-ray, and I figured I would save myself some money since I was not dying to see it. In some ways that may have contributed to me loving the film so much after only a couple of viewings. It's definitely my new favorite Western, as hard as that may be to believe. Rango takes many aspects from classic Westerns and reiterates them through fresh, and often funny ways. I'll briefly summarize the plot. The story revolves around a pet chameleon (voiced by Johnny Depp at the top of his game) who becomes stranded in the Mojave Desert after his terrarium is thrown from his owner's car. After meeting an armadillo named Roadkill (voiced by Alfred Molina), who is seeking the mystical Spirit of the West, he narrowly avoids being eaten by a hawk before meeting another lizard, named Beans (voiced by Isla Fisher). Beans then takes Rango to Dirt, a small, Old West town populated by a colorful cast of various species of desert animals (watch the "Real Creatures of Dirt" featurette in the extras to see their real-life counterparts), whom each has their own different personality, look, and shall I say, walk? That's a joke that ties into an early gag when Rango first arrives at Dirt. There is quite a bit of quirky, offbeat humor throughout, and that caught me off guard. I had a lot of fun watching this movie. More so than I expected to. I have to say, this may just be the most gorgeously animated film that I have ever seen.It's my dream to be an animator and a visual effects artist after I finish college, and to witness the magnificent work on display in this film was a real treat. This may be controversial because Pixar is backed by legions of fans (myself included), but honestly, if ILM (Industrial Light and Magic) worked on more animated films, they would dominate the industry. It's quite funny to me that the very same visual effects house (founded by none other than George Lucas) that gave us Pixar, arguably the best in the business at what they do (which is the whole package of story and animation, not just animation), has made one of the few films that I think looks more visually arresting than anything they have done. It's also ironic that this film is so beautiful, because it has the ugliest cast of characters that I have ever seen in an animated film. Not only the characters, but the scenery has a rugged beauty as well. In the town, Dirt, Gore Verbinski (Director) said that he didn't want any parallel lines or 90 degree angles. He wanted it to show that this ugly little town was not made by expert craftsmen. It was made by animals. It's so incredibly rich and detailed that it's hard not to ogle at it. There are some very well-done action sequences in this film, and I must say that the bat scene is not to be missed. It's quite obvious that this movie is not aiming its focus at little children, in more ways than one. The director himself said so on the commentary, but before I listened to that, I thought that. First of all, as I already mentioned, these characters are not visually appealing, so they probably won't want a plush doll of any of them, except for maybe Rango. He literally is the only character in the film with some color.Another reason why I felt this film was not aiming itself at children was the writing itself. There are so many big words throughout this film that even some older kids and adults will have to look them up. Definitely a few lines that parents will have to explain to their kids later. I can hear it now. "Mommy, what's a prostate?" "Oh, um, I'll tell you in a few years..." "Okay, but what about a mammogram?" "Oh dear God, this is supposed to be a cartoon." And that's where the parent would be wrong. If ever there was a perfect example that not all animated films are for little children, Rango would be it. In one of the bonus features, Verbinski said a quote that I have said a few times, so it really stood out to me. He said, "Animation is not a genre. It's a technique to tell a story." I wish more people would understand this, because it's disappointing when someone won't even give an animated film a chance because they think it's for little kids. On another note, film buffs should, especially Western buffs, should have a ball looking for all of the references to other films, none of which a kid would catch (wink, wink). I definitely couldn't catch them all, so I looked them up. I'll name the ones I found (without spoiling what parts they appear in). There are references to: The Man With No Name Trilogy (referenced quite a few times, in various ways), John Wayne cowboy films in general, Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas, Chinatown, Cat Ballou, High Noon, The Shakiest Gun in the West, Apocalypse Now, Pirates of the Caribbean, Aliens. As you can see, there are plenty to look for, and that probably isn't all of them. Rango is exciting, charming, funny, and fresh. I will definitely be returning to it many times in the coming years.There is no reason to go into great detail here. The movie has enough detail to the point where the animators could probably have taken out a bit of the various textures and fine details, and the movie would probably still be ahead of its competition. The picture quality is simply flawless (no exaggeration). If there was a level above perfection, Rango would be there. I've already said enough about how beautiful and detailed the animations are, and the transfer brings it life very, very well. I'd recommend this Blu-ray just as a reference to show off to friends and family who still buy DVDs. I'd be willing to bet my left nut that it would convert at least one of them. Rescue one of them from the Dark Side. All kidding aside, it truly is a sight to behold. I also want to commend the creators for not succumbing to the 3D craze, and filming Rango in 3D. Even though we always have a choice as to whether or not we want to watch a film in the format, and I pretty much always choose to watch animated films in 3D (so forgive my hypocrisy), it's undeniable that filmmakers spend time tinkering with the 3D that they would otherwise have spent on another aspect of the film. So I'm happy that all of their time was spent perfecting other aspects of Rango. As for the audio, it's top notch as well. Admittedly, I don't have the greatest sound system, but I did not notice any glaring flaws with the audio either, so I have to say it's flawless as well. The extras are also pretty damn good. I almost never watch extras right after the film ends, but I did with Rango.I started with the "Real Creatures of Dirt" featurette. It was actually pretty cool. It was a fairly short (about the length of a half hour TV show with no commercials) and was in the style of the old Zoboomafoo show from PBS, with a Steve Irwin twist (dangerously close, in other words). Next up was the "Breaking the Rules: Making Animation History" featurette, which was your standard "Making of" fair. Both were fun to watch, and will definitely strengthen your love for the film if you like it. It was quite interesting to see the creative way they filmed the actors on a sound stage acting out the entire film, then used the footage for reference when doing the animations. It was almost like motion capture, without the tights suits and little dot markers. Johnny Depp is hilarious to watch. His facial expressions really sell his commitment to the character. I also listened to the audio commentary. It was fun to listen to, and while fans will learn a few interesting tidbits here and there, I wouldn't say it's a necessity. So, all in all, Rango is an all-around satisfying film. It's funny and witty, with fresh humor that isn't often found in animated films. It's often exciting with thrilling chases and square-offs (as all great Westerns do). It has gorgeous scenery (some of the most realistic CGI environments that I have ever seen). And most importantly, it should be entertaining for the whole family, but adults should get more out of it than young children, I give Rango my highest recommendation. MUST OWN.
summary: Quirky Humor, and Not So Cute Characters

reviewText: Rango(released March /11) features the voice talents of,among many others,Alfred Molina,Ned Beatty,Bill Nighy,Harry Dean Stanton and of course Johnny Depp.Depp takes the lead voice as the chameleon who takes on the Rango name and ultimately becomes the unwitting hero in a town that badly needs one.The film is not a release from a major animation studio like Pixar but made/financed through Nickelodeon & GK films,along with Blind Wink.However it has every bit the quality of any other animation studio going and is beautiful and rich in its detail.The film opens as a chameleon is standing in a terrarium,acting out a strange play with inanimate objects that surround him.This is definitely an animal without a life.Suddenly his whole world changes as a sudden stop sends his terrarium crashing onto the hot black tar road,where he is left abandoned.There he meets up with an armadillo who has recently been run over,evidenced by his middle,which has been flattened to the road.The armadillo is a sage of sorts who offers the chameleon some words of advice in his quest for his true self.the chameleon makes it across the road to the desert,where he wanders until he meets an iguana driving a wagon called Beans.She takes him to the town of Dirt.In Dirt water is like gold and the populace there long for the day when it becomes plentiful as it once did.In the local saloon,he has a confrontation with a tuffy there and he adopts the name of Rango from then on.He is also given the job of Sheriff by the towns mayor,a tortoise.It seems the mayor thought he could control Rango,but Rango takes his position with the utmost seriousness.The only source of water left in town is in the bank vault.One night Rango intercepts two prairie dogs digging to get into the bank,caught far short,out in the street.Not twigging on to their real intent,Rango ends up giving them the proper equipment along with the proper digging permit.Next day the water has disappeared out of the bank vault(no surprise),and Rango organizes a posse to find them.They all end up underground following a huge water pipe.This eventually brings them to the home of the prairie dogs and the huge water dispenser that was stolen.It turns out the dispenser is empty.Someone got to it before they did,but who? More detective work takes them near Las Vegas where the valve from which the underground pipes lead to,has been turned off.It seems the mayor and his cronies who have been running Dirt for years,have been hoarding the water for themselves and using it as a control carrot on the rest of the townspeople.The valve is turned back on and before you know it the entire town and surrounding area is water saturated for the first time in years.The mayors control,and life,comes crashing down around his ears and Rango becomes Dirts hero.Deft in script and animation,the film does start off rather slowly as we start to learn about this strange actor wanna be/chameleon.Once he hits the desert,the film picks up considerably and never stops until the end.There is alot of humour here that would go over the head of youngsters and as it comes in at 111 minutes in length,I doubt whether the younger set could sit still long enough to stay with this film.There are alot of neat touches though like the Mariachi Owl band that comes in and out of the film,singing of Rango and his imminent death,and Rango's meeting with the Man with No Name or the legendary Spirit of the West.This is,of course,Clint Eastwood's famous character(voiced by Tim Olyphant).He is dressed in his Man with No name regalia from his 60s movies,with a metal detector in hand and driving a golf cart with his OSCARS in the back!Now I know there are few if any younger than twenty years old that would get that reference.Technically speaking the film is clear and crisp,the animation just awesome and it is in its original w/s a/r.Extras include a featurette on the real denizens of the desert,the original theatrical and extended versions and 10 deleted scenes.In point of fact,the deleted scenes here are just those extras from the extended version.All in all a recommended animation charmer.Depp is wonderful as the lead lizard here,and the world of Dirt and the intrigue of the films plot,keep you interested from the moment he enters the town to the end of the film.Above all the animation is superb.
summary: 3 1/2 -4 stars for this lovable animated entry!

reviewText: Rango (Gore Verbinski, 2011)Rango is something very rare in the current American culture: an animated movie created specifically for grown-ups. Thankfully, it's also brilliant, the kind of movie that provides hard evidence that such a thing can still work in American film culture. Artistically, at least; while the movie performed relatively well at the box office, it didn't make back its budget theatrically. I hope that doesn't doom Industrial Light and Magic's animation department to the dustbin, because Rango is the best American animated movie in a decade.Plot: Rango (voice of Johnny Depp)—though he is not named Rango at the beginning of the film (he is unnamed in the first part of the film, and this is not trivial)—is a pet chameleon on a roadtrip through the desert when a near-miss car accident sends his tank out of his owners' RV. The previously-pampered pet with an acting aspiration very quickly learns that the outside world is a different place indeed than he is used to. After an encounter with the  plucky, if somewhat insane, Beans (Now You See Me's Isla Fisher), he accompanies her back to her hometown of Dirt, where he spins a few tall tales and somehow finds himself talked into accepting the job of town sheriff. Can the newly-christened Rango use his chameleon nature to truly become the brave, heroic lizard he has made himself out to be, save the town's dwimdling water supply, and stand up to local villain Rattlesnake Jake (Hot Fuzz' Bill Nighy)?Impeccable comic timing (it's obvious Verbinski took the Robin-Williams-in-Aladdin approach here of “give the cast their scripts, let them ad-lib their hearts out, and then animate around it”), gorgeously detailed animation, dozens of in-jokes for movie buffs. Rango has pretty much everything you could want in a comedy. And while the kiddies will certainly enjoy the bright colors and the chaos, this is old-school-Looney-Tunes humor, written with the intelligence and wit to be funny enough for the kids but with veiled (and sometimes not so veiled) more adult humor lying just underneath the surface for the adults as well. This is phenomenal stuff; if you missed it the first time around, rent it now. ****

reviewText: Every now and then a movie comes along that jumpstarts a genre that has grown tedious, tired and torpid.  Witness the stream of 3-D computer-generated animations that beg for our attention.  And then Rango saunters onto the scene.  Like the dry wasteland this self-proclaimed lizard hero enters, so is the domain of contending cgi comic iterations assaulting our senses.The first daring and glorious decision the cool kids at Nickelodeon and Blind Wink made was to forgo 3-D for a bright, crisp, highly detailed and daringly artistic two dimensional world that verges between the merely surreal and a full-blown lucid fever dream.  I couldn't help but think of Carlos Costeneda.Directed with a loose hand by Gore Verbinski from a terrifically unhinged screenplay by John Logan (THE AVIATOR) the story follows a pet lizard, a terrarium-bound, hipster, stand-up chameleon in a Hawaiian shirt (and no pants) with dreams of going on a hero's adventure a la Joseph Campbell's mythic conceit.  Suddenly, out of the blue, an accident thrusts him into his adventure.  Rango goes without a name for a while and then defines himself as western gunslinger Rango who will save the town of Dirt from its manufactured drought.  Yes, Rango is true to the beats of the mythic hero's journey and true to form, finally brings the elixir to the desperate town's inhabitants of semi-civilized varmints and assorted desert dwellers -- all of whom are voiced and designed with a finesse rarely seen.The thing that I really liked about Rango -- the character and the movie -- is that all the self-referential material, the homages and the sly winks to the adult audience never seemed in any way contrived or condescending.  It was part of the tapestry from frame one.Rango is a terrific icon of our shared, post-modern, existential dilemma of not being able to escape our own story.  I love that.  But ironically, the film allows us to do just that - even if for only 90 or so minutes.  Don't miss this sly masterpiece about how to dream and live the life you desire.

reviewText: Remember when Gore Verbbinsky and Johnny Depp first got together and made Pirates of the Caribbean?  The first movie was so good, the second movie seemed like they started filming without finishing the script, and by the third film, it seemed like the camera was just rolling and nobody bothered at all.  Rango feels like the two of them were talking and said, "you know what we should do?  An animated film!"  and the other one said, "Yeah, let's make it a western. that will be cool."  But then, they never really got any further than that story wise.To be fair, it's a bit more story than Pirates three, but not one that needed to be told.  There is a really odd scene where the entire town becomes zombie-like and starts a creepy line dance and no explanation is given as to why they acted that way.  Just more in-cohesiveness.On the other hand, the animation is by none other than ILM and it's the best I've seen from anyone.  So, see it if you really like animation or if you really, really like Johnny Depp.  So it's not awful, but it's just not compelling either.

reviewText: Cleaning up Dirt!  Rango Rides!What a fun film!Rango (we never really find out his real name) has created a fantasy world inside his little terrarium, being an actor and his stage  includes a headless Barbie doll, a wind-up goldfish, a tree and a lake.  An unfortunate accident throws him out of his interior world and though he does not know it yet, gives him the purpose he has always craved.After some chat with a philosophical armadillo, he makes it to Dirt, a western town that must copy stereotypical characters from just about every western film you've ever seen, which is a good thing!Animation:I loved this animation!  Pixar look out!  The attention to detail down to the fire sparks from burned logs, sand and water, even pupils dilating.  Amazing detail and all in glorious 2D (remember 2D?)!Fav Scenes:The story has a few nods to other films that the older viewers may catch, including a parody of Apocalypse Now, with flying bats playing Ride of the Valkeries as they shoot up the good guys trying to get their stolen water back.Rango is an actor and convinces the town that he is a hero and through a few lucky breaks such as killing the local hawk that has been dining on the citizens, they all consider him so.  The slimy mayor however has other plans and is dealing a vicious hand to the detriment of the whole town.  There are some slapstick moments, and a few lines are hilarious:"Is this heaven?""No.  Eating PopTarts with Kim Novak is heaven!"Themes:Pretending to be someone you're not may get you aways, but really finding out who you really are is a start to respect for yourself and others.  Bad guys are not necessarily all bad and can work with you for a common cause.  And finally, those who take advantage of others' needs (the town and its lack of water) will eventually fail.  Karma, you know.Film's Aftermath:The theater was packed with families.  When I left, I heard one man exclaim that this is the most fun he has had in a theater in a long time.  Quite a testimonial.  Clearly this film will be nominated for Best Animated Feature -- but we have the rest of the year to go!  Great start!Cast & Crew:Directed byGore VerbinskiWriting creditsJohn Logan(screenplay)John Logan(story)Gore Verbinski(story)James Ward Byrkit(story)Cast (in credits order)Johnny Depp...  Rango / Lars (voice)Isla Fisher...  Beans (voice)Abigail Breslin...  Priscilla (voice)Ned Beatty...  Mayor (voice)Alfred Molina...  Roadkill (voice)Bill Nighy...  Rattlesnake Jake (voice)
summary: Rango Cleans Up "Dirt" In This Fun Family Feature!

reviewText: When the Lizard with no name strode into the dry town of Dirt, it would change both of them forever! Dirt: a backwater, no-water, lawless outpost of the old west, and Rango: a terrarium bred chameleon with thespian ambitions. When Rango's fast mouth gets the better of him he finds you can't just talk your way into being a hero.And...Rango is an adult Western. Doesn't matter about the sumptuously animated characters or the beautifully realised backgrounds what we have here, pure and simple, is Shane, the Dollars Westerns of Sergio Leone and any number of generic archetypes you care to name (The Three Amigos also comes to mind!) As such i'm a little confused as to who the target audience for Rango is. There is nothing cute here to sell to the kiddies - no cuddly toys or lunch boxes to promote, far too many adults also still think animation is somehow sub-par film making and it will pass them by, it hasn't been advertised much as a Western so fans there are likely to miss out. Which leaves only rabid Johnny Depp and Gore Verbinski fans (connoisseurs!) and that's a great shame as Rango is a brilliant movie aimed far more at an adult and Western fans audience than at the child/teen market.All the best bits go completely over the heads of the younger audience. The whole Western pastiche will be unfamiliar to many: extreme, frame filling close ups, dirty saloons, fast talking, mariachi music, swearing and death! The 'Spirit of the West' left nearly all the adults in the theatre spitting popcorn ad laughing. The earlier "Fear and Loathing" skit cracked up another significant proportion of the adult audience leaving the kids scratching their heads. Bill Nighy steals every scene turning in an Oscar worthy performance as the genuinely scary (scary as in: will give children nightmares scary) Rattlesnake Jake: "Go to hell!" "Where d'you think i come from?" Ned Beatty adds considerable menace as the mayor and even the overall characterisation and design errs more on the side of harsh reality than fluffy fancyisms.The overarching theme of a town of animals in the Nevada desert, bled dry of water by the march of 'progress', will also pass many by; but may also plant a few seeds ;)The film does have plenty to satisfy older children too. But for once it is these bits that feel like they have been shoe-horned into an adult movie, rather than vice versa. As such Rango falls between two stools being neither dramatic nor intelligent enough to be a genuine adult pastiche, nor foolishly funny or endearing enough to satisfy children. However the good bits are genius and the bad bits merely 'just' entertaining which gives Rango real 5-star appeal!

reviewText: Rango is a brilliantly designed film. It's a western, starring desert animals that look every inch the part. It is a triumph of character design, drawing on a vastly underutilized subset of the animal kingdom. The casting is note perfect. Toads, possums, lizards, tortoises, and the deadliest rattlesnake gunslinger this side of the Rio Grande. Desert animals tend to be scaly, bumpy, and scruffy, and they seem so at home in the mining colony of Dirt, it makes other talking creature movies look like they were designed by plush animal companies. The irony is that if they ever made toy action figures of those mariachi owls, I would buy mine in a heart beat.The story is rather simple. It's the same plot from A Bug's Life, which is the same plot as The Brave Little Tailor. A newcomer (recently escaped lizard Rango) is mistaken for a hero to help solve the town's big problem. in this case, it's a lack of water. Had the movie simply stuck with this tried and true narrative, it could have become one of the all time greats.Instead, the filmmakers seemed determined to load it down with weird quirky bits that look like they belong in a Wes Anderson film. Rango's lizard love interest has a brain glitch that causes her to space out for minutes on end. There's a bizarre homage to Eastwood's Man With No Name, who drives around in a golf cart. The townsfolk line up to perform a strange rain dance every Wednesday. Rango himself spends the first several minutes of the movie putting on an odd one-man show before his aquarium is tossed out the window. These episodes add nothing to film, and only serve to jar us out of the expertly realized Wild West.The bits that work best are based on those time-honored motifs. Rango leading his posse out into desert in search of bank robbers. A runaway wagon chase, with a hundred bats in pursuit. Facing down that slimy rattlesnake at high noon. Too bad that storytellers want to keep busting up these scenes with walking cactus spirits and mystic roadkill. Rango is definitely a beautiful film to watch. It just could have used some tighter focus.
summary: Fantastic Desert Critters Nearly Undermined by Too Much Quirkiness

reviewText: Rango is a Western that has a chameleon in the premier spot; he's the star of the show. Rango comes from humble beginnings (falls out of his family's car while traveling) and is thrown headlong into a role as a sheriff for a desert town trying to figure out where the water they once got every Wednesday, seems to have dried up.Predictable is one way to describe this. It's also sold as a children's movie, having Nickelodeon's name attached, but with all the "hell's" being tossed around, I don't know how many parents would want their younger children to view this.Over all it was an OK movie, at best. The film gets 2-3 stars, tops. The Blu Ray gets 5 stars for its presentation.This disc is region free, so you can enjoy it anywhere in the world if purchased through Amazon USA.Video-Encoded in AVC, this HD video will probably be a movie worthy of showcasing just what your shiny new HD TV is capable of. The colors are spot on, there are no video anomalies. Bit rate is high. The movie was done in 2.35:1 ratio, so on your 16x9 HD TV you will still have black borders on the top and bottom of the image.The video quality is "jaw hit the floor" amazing. 5 stars for video.Audio-DTS-HD MA (for those that don't know the lingo, this is super high quality). Despite it being a multichannel, 5.1 mix, most of the sound will be driven by your front sound stage and mostly the center channel as the show really is dialog driven.You also get Spanish, Portuguese, and French 5.1 audio. I only did a light sampling of these audio tracks given I don't understand a lick of any of the language. The only thing that seems to change is the language; none of the music or effects change, which is as it should be.5 stars for audioExtras-Audio commentary (self explanatory), Real Creatures of Dirt (live action dip into the real life inspirations for the creatures of Dirt, the town in the film) and deleted scenes. If you watch the extended version of the film, all 10 of the deleted scenes will be shown during the film, so this extra may not seem like an "extra" to some.4 stars for the extras. There isn't a lot there, but what is there is nice.Packaging-Rango comes with an embossed cardboard slip cover that covers the standard Blu Ray case. It looks nice. 4 stars as it is nothing amazing.Also of note is the extra DVD. This DVD is ONLY the theatrical version of the film; it does NOT contain the extended edition that restores the cut scenes to the film or the extras. There is also a digital version of the film included for those who wish to transfer to their iPod/iPhone/whatever. This is also the theatrical, non-extended version of the film.Over all, what you get from Rango will depend. If you get all the visual jabs (or nods) at other films, such as Star Wars, Fear and Loathing, etc, you'll enjoy the film immensely. If you're a child, you're likely to feel this movie is potentially boring and has some "bad" language. If you don't get all the nods/jabs and you're not a kid, you will probably only be mildly amused, as I was, by the film.You'll probably want to sample the movie, either via streaming (if it's available) or that DVD/Blu Ray via that monthly DVD subscription before buying to make sure it's something you will watch with any frequency.Film is 3 stars at most. Blu Ray is, hands down, 5 stars.
summary: Movie is kinda iffy, transfer is amazing

reviewText: I had high expectations after seeing this in theaters and knowing ILM material is made ideally for a format like Blu Ray, and without hesitation this is the best animated Blu I have seen since HD started.I am skipping the (for a better word) animated discussions about all of the hate and discontent towards this film, instead this is merely a product review. The picture and sound are flawless - as perfect as I have heard or seen on a film like this. Every frame is virtually a reference point for a multitude of factors, and the sound uses EVERY channel repeatedly; this is by far the movie to show off your home theater to friends with. The supplements are full of information and can be a worthy time investment (be sure to check the last one for the kids):* Extended version, 4 minutes longer. After watching both versions several times to try and catch the little differences, I painfully became aware I could have watched the deleted scenes to get the answer of what was changed (grrrr). All of the removals are even raunchier adult-themed jokes and material (the Tony Bennett one was funny though). The majority of the added-in footage is the last 3 minutes of the film - essentially an alternate adult ending.* Commentary by the minds behind the film (extended version only). I preferred the documentary with these guys in it as there were too many participants for this commentary.* Deleted scenes, 8:27 minutes in HD. All of these are actually what makes the extended version (them adding the footage on each beginning/start of the scenes is what makes this longer).* Storyboard PiP reel, rated version. Once again I liked the documentaries over watching this but it does contain some great artwork.* Behind the scenes, 2 docus totaling 48:52 minutes. These show the whole pre-production process, from the brainstorming sit-downs to the "dramaturgical" events leading up to this film being created. Lists the westerns here that inspired this film (High Noon (Collector's Edition),Will Penny,True Grit (Special Collector's Edition)). Always nice to watch the ILM crew do their art here.* Real creatures of Dirt, 22:10 minutes. Follows one of those Animal Planet insane guys as he tracks down the critters in the desert and does crazy things while talking about them ("this is the most deadly animal in the desert - here let me pick him up while he strikes at me"). Fun for kids.* Field trip to Dirt, takes a couple hours. This life-like program allows you to advance your way through the town. You pick which direction you want to go and into what building. Inside each area are character descriptions and artwork. This was a great time killer in the store as kids tracked their way through all parts of the town - no cheap animation here either, best supplement I have seen for graphics and interest level for the kids.* Disc 2 - bare bones DVD.The movie does cause some parents to get all ruffled while I play it in the store, but I love the adult themes of this movie and obviously the picture sells itself and the sound gives your home theater a good workout. Hope you take the time to avoid all of the negative feedback out there, see that these guys were trying to make a film catered towards older kids and adults - and maybe you might get a fun viewing out of it.
summary: Amazing Blu, a beautiful film, worthy product to own

reviewText: Rango (animation, comedy, adventure)Directed by Gore VerbinskiStarring the voices of Johnny Depp, Isla Fisher, Bill Nighy and Ned BeattyParamount Pictures | 2011 | 112 min | Rated PG | Released Jul 15, 2011Video:Video codec: MPEG-4 AVCVideo resolution: 1080pAspect ratio: 2.40:1Audio:English: DTS-HD Master Audio 5.1French: Dolby Digital 5.1Portuguese: Dolby Digital 5.1Spanish: Dolby Digital 5.1Subtitles:English, English SDH, French, Portuguese, SpanishDiscs:50GB Blu-ray DiscDVD copy (with digital copy)The Film 4/5The Blu-ray includes the 107-minute theatrical version and a 112-minute extended version.Rango (Depp) is an aquatic chameleon who is trying to discover his purpose in life. He lives alone in a tank until the car it is being transported in hits a bump and gives him his freedom in the desert. His journey begins when he discovers an armadillo and is told to visit the nearby town of Dirt if he wants to find water. He's given a ride by Beans (Fisher), who owns land in the valley and drops him off in town.Rango begins the movie as a liar who is unsure of his capabilities, until dumb luck elevates him in the eyes of the locals and he starts to believe in himself. He represents hope as the townspeople struggle to find the water they need to survive.The first part of the story is not particularly encouraging. It moves at a frantic pace and initially relies on characters being hurt, and belch or fart jokes for comic relief. But things eventually settle down and the story starts to work. It references many movies from the Western genre, including True Grit and High Noon. Some scenes pay tribute to other movies such as Star Wars.The story is simple, but the setting and design of the characters is extremely detailed. There's also a wealth of voice talent in the supporting cast, including Ray Winstone, Harry Dean Stanton, Abigail Breslin and Timothy Olyphant, as well as the main cast.The dialogue isn't typical and a lot of it won't be easily understood by children. The characters mention chromosome pools, paradigm shifts and aquifers. Rango, in particular, is very articulate. It's quite refreshing to see this kind of thing in an animated movie. Maybe some of the kids will ask their parents to explain terms they don't understand. Even though some of the dialogue is complex, the story is easy to follow.The movie is a mix of fast-paced action, dumb jokes, clever jokes, battle scenes and quiet moments in which Rango contemplates his existence. There are problems to be solved, misunderstandings and traditional themes of good versus evil. One of my favorite elements is the use of a mariachi band, composed of four owls, documenting Rango's tale through the use of various songs.I won't reveal any more of the plot, but I found Rango to be an enjoyable ride. The first 30 minutes had me worried because of the pacing and the dumb jokes, but things improve significantly in the last hour. I often have problems adjusting to the style of North American animation after seeing one of Hayao Miyazaki's films, and I viewed Spirited Away a few days ago. Once I accepted that Rango was a totally different style; I started to enjoy it more.  It's not perfect, but it's well worth your time.Video Quality 5/5If you've ever seen a Pixar movie on Blu-ray, you'll have an idea what to expect from Rango. I couldn't detect a single fault. Colors are striking and detail is exceptional. All of the backgrounds seem properly finished and add depth to the image. When you see Rango's face at the start of the movie, it looks like he's in the room with you. Clothing, skin, scenery and water are all displayed perfectly. This is a presentation that shows off the Blu-ray format wonderfully. Nobody will be disappointed with the look of the movie.Audio Quality 5/5The DTS-HD Master Audio 5.1 track doesn't disappoint either. There's a lot going on throughout the movie and the lossless audio handles everything well. Some of the battle scenes are particularly loud, while other scenes rely on music for maximum effect. The rear speakers are used frequently and I didn't detect any faults in the mix. The image will dazzle you, but you'll be happy with the sound too.Special Features 4/5The additional features are all presented in full HD.Audio Commentary (Extended version only) with Director, Gore Verbinski; Head of Story James Ward Byrkit; Production Designer Mark "Crash" McCreery; Animation Director Hal Hickel; and Visual Effects Supervisor Tim Alexander.Breaking the Rules: Making Animation History (48:52) - A two-part feature consisting of The Stage is Set and Now we Ride. Learn about how the movie was made and see the evolution of the characters.Deleted Scenes (8:27) - A brief look at 10 additional scenes which will seem very familiar if you watched the extended version of the movie.Real Creatures of Dirt (22:15) - Showing real desert creatures such as snakes, scorpions, tarantulas and armadillos.Storyboard Reel Picture-in-Picture (theatrical version only)A Field Trip to Dirt - An interactive digital model which allows you to ride through the town and look around.Theatrical Trailer (2:27)CreditsPreviewsDVD Copy (digital copy on disc)Rango is a fun way to spend almost two hours. Although some of the dialogue is complex, the movie is suitable for the whole family and has something for everyone. The blend of action and humor works well overall and the animals make interesting and memorable characters. The Blu-ray is just about perfect and Rango immediately ranks among the best presentations the format has to offer.Overall score 4.5/5
summary: An entertaining animated Western for the whole family

reviewText: This is a typical hard-boiled Western transposed onto desert wildlife, using some rather impressive computer animation (the textures have a level of realism I have never seen before), and a few big name actors, including a clever cameo/impesonation by the king of the hard-boiled Western. (If you don't know, I don't want to spoil it.)Too talky and complicated for young kids (the MANY old movie references will obviously sail right over their heads; heck I'm in my mid-30s and most of the references are well before my time and likely only to appeal to Western film buffs), and not fleshed out enough for adults, with some nonsensical touches that distracted from the story. Why are all the animals in the town the same size--cats and lizards, for instance--and wearing clothes, when the story is clearly set in the real, human world and animals/people outside Dirt are animated to scale? And why are some animals characters, while others, seemingly of the same class and species, livestock?  On the one hand, the animals relied on converted human objects to build their towns, and then on the other they seemed to have their own industries and imports, for things like lizard-sized wagons and a cactus juice bottling plant. The fantasy-reality mix just didn't seem to fit.As a viewer, if I'm thinking about all this while watching the movie, it's because the story hasn't drawn me in enough to overlook these lapses in logic. Not to mention the fact that the film's climax completely skips how the water was diverted in the first place, and has no resolve to the what-the-mayor-is-buying-up-farms-to-build storyline that dominates the whole rest of the film. (Kind of a big plot hole. Though I guess we're supposed to imagine he's building a Lizard Las Vegas?) And,  yeah, the Wednesday water scene was creepy/weird and totally out of character from the rest of the film. Those were the good old Zombie days (when the spigot turned) the townsfolk wanted to recapture?In an attempt, I'm sure, to appeal to kids, the story is a bit too dumbed down for grown-ups, but still definitely over most kids' heads. And while, as I mentioned before, the animation is top-notch realistic, that also leads to some needlessly scary scenes for kids under, say, 7. I just didn't get the "it's so smart" vibe that many who seem to love it did. I thought it was, actually, pretty wishy-washy about its message, appeal and perspective. -While this wasn't a terrible movie, it wasn't really for kids OR adults, and therefore just felt flat, despite a few funny and clever moments and some truly amazing animation.
summary: Too Much for Kids, Not Enough for Adults

reviewText: I don't know how to define Rango. I went to the movie theater with my 6 year old daughter expecting to see a funny movie about a chameleon and was served something completely unexpected. The trailer showing an eagle hunting our poor chameleon must be the most misleading trailer ever.This movie is not for kids. At least not for the ones younger than 10 years old or so. It is mature and it has very adult concepts (the dream sequence, for example) dispersed throughout.First the technical merits: Rango is beautiful to behold. The animated characters are all great. Quirky and lovable. This is one animation you will love watching.When it comes to the story, it must be said that things start pretty slowly. That's where you start seeing younger children starting to lose interest. The pace picks up in the middle; then slows a little once again before the finale. It is about a a lonely, delusional misfit who tries to find his place in the world. Much like any one of us. Except that he is a chameleon surrounded by evil moles and snakes and turtles and what not.If I had gone to the movie alone it would have been a great experience. With my daughter, I was a bit uneasy knowing she wasn't getting all of the story. Mind you, my daughter is quite perceptive but I do not expect her to understand the backstory of Rango.Nevertheless, this is a serious movie which is animated. Don't regard it as a children's movie and you will like it just fine.
summary: This is not a good kids' movie but a good adult movie

reviewText: Rango is a very unique animated film that I honestly don't think I can evaluate by traditional animation standards.  Yes, it is animated (a good first outing for special effect giant Industrial Light And Magic, for whom this is their first fully animated film) and yes, there is lots of slapstick material for the family audience, but the true intended audience of Rango is clearly more seasoned moviegoers.  This is an animated film I think will be most appreciated by those who are familiar with the many films it draws inspiration from. Director Gore Verbinski switches gears from his Pirates of the Caribbean trilogy, which had gotten pretty over-the-top by At World's End to deliver a light, enjoyable animated feature.Johnny Depp is the titular "Rango" - or, at least, that's who he claims to be.  You see, the chameleon was a family pet with an overactive imagination who dreamed of writing plays and acting out heroic characters, but whose true name the audience is never given (no doubt a nod to the Man with No Name western trilogy starring Clint Eastwood).  When he gets lost due to a freak accident in the Mojave Desert his travels take him to the small animal community of Dirt he quickly forges a false identity under the name "Rango"- a rough, gun blazing icon who once killed seven men with a single bullet!  By chance he also manages to kill the hawk (which happens to sport a steel tipped beak) which only raises his prestige in the town, resulting in his becoming the new town sheriff.Johnny Depp gives a very enjoyable performance as Rango, but I don't think is as "likable" as the script seems to want him to be- or I should say: he isn't likable in the way a "family movie" hero should be likable.  He is often cowardly, self-centered, as well as a compulsive liar whose imagination runs rampant.  One scene in particular stands out for Rango's "unlikable" factor, when the citizens of Dirt are rioting over the water shortage and Rango (who has been thirsty most of the movie) chooses to drink four cups of water while lecturing the citizens on how they can't all get water or else they'd run out.  Naturally he looks like a perfect ass for this entire segment that can't really be sympathized with by the audience.  This is fun for older audiences who like a more flawed protagonist, but at times the script tries too hard to make him seem like a charming, upstanding role-model, when lots of the time he just comes across as a jerk.Most important to know about before seeing Rango is undoubtedly Sergio Leone's Italian made Westerns (Or "Spaghetti Westerns" as we lovingly tend to call them), particularly the ones featuring Clint Eastwood in his break out role as The Man with No Name.  The music, the look, the atmosphere, and the classic western stand-offs are all in loving tribute of Leone's heavily stylized portrayal of the west.  Aside from the pure Leone Western clichés and archetypes the primary plot of Rango surprisingly is taken from Roman Polanski's detective mystery Chinatown.  In both the plot revolves around a city (the small desert community of "Dirt" replaces L.A.) that is experiencing a severe draught, yet someone is dumping fresh, usable water into the desert, away from the eyes of citizens for some unknown reason.  If you have seen "Chinatown", Rango makes no attempt of hiding who the antagonist will turn-out to be, as the villain dresses the same as the villain of Chinatown, and has the EXACT same plan involving water and real-estate, but that isn't really bothersome because Rango puts a lot of heart in its tributes to classic films.  They know that they're using Chinatown's plot and I don't think they try to sell this film's plot as being anything other than an excuse to pay tribute to the classics, so this isn't a problem,The secondary antagonist of the film is the one who's already been revealed via trailers: A leather hat wearing serpent by the name of Rattlesnake Jake.  Coming out with a tough as nails voice and a segmented Gatling gun for a rattle this is honestly perhaps the most awesome villain I've seen in an animated film in years!  He even tells a character that he comes from Hell (oh yeah- this film does take a risk for an animated film of using lots of "Damns" and "Go to Hell!" type talk that parents wouldn't want repeated by their children).  With all the other sentient animals in this film (it will always bug me why some animals in here are anthromorphic and sentient while others, like the roadrunners, are not...) it is really impressive to see how the folk from Industrial Light And Magic were able to bring credibility to a snake being capable of doing the same things as all the other critters, even with the lack of hands.Jake is voiced amazingly well by British actor Bill Nighy, who, like Depp, previously worked with director Gore Verbinski in the Pirates of the Caribbean films, portraying tentacle-faced ship captain Davy Jones.  He really must have had fun doing this outlaw of a Diamondback Rattlesnake (who is so villainous he even has a little moustache pattern on the scales above his mouth!). I'm serious, this villain is just pure fun to watch.  He is every-single awesome outlaw stereotype wrapped up in a delicious, slivering package!  He has a foot (tail?) in for being a likely pick if I choose to compile a list of my favorite villains for the 2011 movie season.Gore Verbenski and composer Hans Zimmer made it apparent that they had a mutual love of Sergio Leone and Ennio Morricone's musical scores.  Once more Zimmer reflects on the themes of "The Good, The Bad, And The Ugly" and "Once Upon A Time In The West" with extraordinary effectiveness.Rango is not a perfect animated movie, nor do I think young children will appreciate it as much as viewers in their upper teens and older.  It won't traumatize any kids, but it probably is far too intense for them, and the best of the film's humor they'll likely have no hope in understanding due to not being exposed to the countless films referenced- many of which are rated R films from the 1960s-1970s.  There's Chinatown and the Leone Spaghetti Westerns, but other films I saw referenced include: Apocalypse Now, Star Wars, The Wizard of Oz, any given zombie movie, and I'm sure there were many more that have simply slipped my mind.As a standalone film I do think Rango was mighty entertaining for what it was- a loving tribute to the western genre and other classic films.
summary: Unique and fitting tribute to the genre
